I'm with you. And that could be translated to "se me parte", although apparently there are many

39
00:02:47,400 --> 00:02:53,120
words that you can use to describe a broken heart. This word could also be pronounced "tear" as in

40
00:02:53,360 --> 00:03:00,340
"save your tears for another day". And the Spanish for that is "lágrima". In this case, there are two

41
00:03:00,600 --> 00:03:05,580
distinct words "tear" and "tear" with different meanings and they look the same but in this case

42
00:03:05,860 --> 00:03:11,740
don't sound the same. When two distinct words have the same spelling and "may" or "may not" have the

43
00:03:11,760 --> 00:03:17,500
pronunciation, these are called homographs. So homonyms are a special case of homographs that

44
00:03:17,680 --> 00:03:22,480
not only look the same but sound the same. You don't need to remember these specific terms when

45
00:03:22,560 --> 00:03:27,780
you're learning about AI, but it helps to remember that when two distinct words at least look the

46
00:03:27,960 --> 00:03:33,080
same, then this can be a challenging task for a machine translation service. Now let's go beyond

47
00:03:33,280 --> 00:03:39,460
single words and look at a sentence. In English, I ate the salad when translated to Hindi is this:

48
00:03:39,680 --> 00:03:44,160
If we don't know anything about Hindi, then we might guess that each of these three words are

49
00:03:44,420 --> 00:03:47,580
I ate the salad. But let's play the audio.

50
00:03:49,540 --> 00:03:54,180
It actually sounds like the middle word is "salad" instead of "ate".

51
00:03:54,300 --> 00:03:59,600
So "I ate the salad" is translated to "many salad kaya".

52
00:03:59,880 --> 00:04:06,700
If you match up the words, "I" is "many the salad" "salad ate" "kaya".

53
00:04:06,800 --> 00:04:09,840
So it's literally "I ate."

54
00:04:10,080 --> 00:04:17,100
In English, sentences follow the pattern "subject", "verb", then the object that the verb is acting on.

55
00:04:17,420 --> 00:04:19,400
"I ate the salad."

56
00:04:19,480 --> 00:04:25,920
In Hindi, the pattern is "subject object verb" as in "I ate."

57
00:04:25,980 --> 00:04:30,120
Japanese is also similar in that the verb comes after the object.

58
00:04:32,080 --> 00:04:36,760
So, word order varies depending on which language you're translating from and to.

59
00:04:37,300 --> 00:04:39,140
Let's look at something called dropped pronouns.

60
00:04:39,640 --> 00:04:43,020
I ate, in English, is yo comi in Spanish.

61
00:04:43,520 --> 00:04:46,220
I ate the salad is comi la ensalada.

62
00:04:46,640 --> 00:04:49,440
Notice that the word yo just disappeared.

63
00:04:49,880 --> 00:04:50,920
Yo, what's up with that?

64
00:04:51,200 --> 00:04:55,460
I ate the fresh salad is comi la ensalada fresca.

65
00:04:55,720 --> 00:04:56,980
Let's take a closer look at this.

66
00:04:57,300 --> 00:05:02,720
The English, I ate the fresh salad, translates in Spanish to yo comi la ensalada fresca.

67
00:05:03,200 --> 00:05:05,880
So this is I ate the salad fresh.

68
00:05:06,420 --> 00:05:08,920
So this is another example of word order differences.

69
00:05:09,420 --> 00:05:12,700
In English, the adjective goes first, followed by the noun.

70
00:05:13,020 --> 00:05:16,840
This is the same for other languages like Chinese, Japanese, and Korean.

71
00:05:17,220 --> 00:05:22,120
In Spanish, the noun comes first, followed by the adjective salad fresh.

72
00:05:22,480 --> 00:05:26,660
This is the same for other languages like French, Arabic, and Hindi.

73
00:05:27,140 --> 00:05:32,120
So again, the word order depends on the language that you're translating from or translating to.

74
00:05:32,500 --> 00:05:35,440
And you may have noticed that the word yo disappeared earlier.

75
00:05:35,980 --> 00:05:40,020
In Spanish, you can drop the pronoun yo and it would read just fine as

76
00:05:40,400 --> 00:05:41,900
Comí la ensalada fresca.

77
00:05:42,260 --> 00:05:47,900
Languages like Spanish, Chinese, and Japanese that let you drop the pronoun in sentences

78
00:05:48,400 --> 00:05:50,260
are called pro-drop languages.

79
00:05:50,640 --> 00:05:52,680
Now, you don't need to remember the term pro-drop,

80
